Core planning rules (must follow):
- Single-fact questions need exactly one node.
- Bridge questions need 2 nodes (one to resolve the bridge entity, one to answer the final target).
- Nested 3+ hop bridge questions need 3–4 nodes chained via depends_on (max depth 3).
- Comparison/intersection across N independent entities use N parallel root nodes plus one synthesizing child node.
- Maximum 6 nodes total, max depth 3.
- Node ids MUST be of the form:
  - Depth-0 siblings: Q1.1, Q1.2, Q1.3, ...
  - Depth-1 nodes (children of any depth-0 node): Q2.1, Q2.2, ...
  - Depth-2 nodes (children of any depth-1 node): Q3.1, Q3.2, ...
- Reference parent answers in a child question with EXACT tags like <A1.1>, <A1.2>, <A2.1>. Do NOT use <AI.Q1> or <Q1>.
- Each node MUST have keys: id, question, expected_type, depends_on.
- depends_on is a JSON list of parent node ids (empty for roots).
- expected_type is one of: person, place, date, number, title, organization, yes_no, entity.
- Output STRICT JSON only with the schema {"nodes": [...], "final_node": "QX.Y"}.

Adaptation to difficulty profiles (use when provided):
- bridge_2hop: 2-node chain (resolve bridge entity -> final target).
- bridge_3hop_plus: Prefer a 3-node chain (or 4 if truly necessary), depth ≤ 3. A reliable pattern is:
  - Resolve the primary subject explicitly (entity grounding/disambiguation).
  - Resolve the bridge entity from that subject.
  - Query the final attribute/target of the bridge entity.
  Example pattern:
  - Q1.1: Who is/which entity is [primary subject]? (person/entity)
  - Q2.1: Who/what is the [bridge relation] of <A1.1>? (person/entity)
  - Q3.1: What/where/when is the [target attribute] of <A2.1>? (type = as needed)
- comparison / intersection: N root facts in parallel + 1 synthesizing child node. Make all independent facts explicit root nodes to enable batching.

Budget awareness (token cost management):
- budget_hint normal: aim for total execution tokens ≤ 8000.
- Keep node questions concise and unambiguous to reduce retrieval/generation cost.
- When multiple independent root facts are required, make them parallel root nodes to enable hop_batch execution downstream.
- Prefer collapsing unnecessary nodes only when budgets are tight or when parallel batching cannot be leveraged without adding value. If a profile expects 3+ hops (e.g., bridge_3hop_plus), favor the 3-node chain unless doing so would clearly exceed budget; then compress carefully while preserving answerability.

Heuristics for robust decomposition (especially on 2WikiMultiHop-style questions):
- If the subject name may be ambiguous (titles, royals, places with qualifiers), add an explicit subject grounding node first in bridge_3hop_plus profiles.
- Use canonical relation phrasings:
  - Kinship: "Who is the mother/father/spouse of X?"
  - Attributes: "Where did X die?" or "What is the place of death of X?" (expected_type=place)
  - Capital/country: "What is the capital of X?" (expected_type=place)
  - Birth/death: "When was X born/died?" (expected_type=date)
- For comparisons: ask for dates/numbers in root nodes, then synthesize in a child node.

Quality and conformance checks before output:
- Ensure the DAG fully determines the final answer with no missing hop.
- Ensure the topology matches the profile (e.g., bridge_3hop_plus => 3-node chain with explicit grounding when applicable).
- Ensure max nodes ≤ 6 and max depth ≤ 3.
- Ensure every child node references parents via exact <A#.#> tags and lists all parents in depends_on.
- Ensure expected_type matches the question target (person/place/date/number/title/organization/yes_no/entity).
- Output strict JSON only (no extra text).

Illustrative mapping for a “X’s mother’s place of death” under bridge_3hop_plus:
- Q1.1: Who is X? (person/entity) depends_on:[]
- Q2.1: Who is the mother of <A1.1>? (person) depends_on:["Q1.1"]
- Q3.1: Where did <A2.1> die? (place) depends_on:["Q2.1"]
final_node: "Q3.1"
