- When two bridges are independent, suggest hop_batch (parallel retrieval) instead of chained 3-hop DAGs.
- Use topology tags: chain_n2 or dag_n2 (if dependencies) or hop_batch (if parallel).
- If temporal constraints exist (e.g., “during Y”, “when he died”), tag temporal.
- Include the expected answer_type to help downstream validation: entity | number | date | yes_no | list.

Answer-type cues:
- Who/Which (person) -> answer_type=entity.
- What (work/thing/place) -> answer_type=entity.
- How many/much/on average/how often -> answer_type=number.
- When -> answer_type=date.
- Is/Are/Do/Does -> answer_type=yes_no (route easy only if direct named-entity attributes suffice).

Use profile when provided:
- profile=bridge_2hop → hard; hops=2; topology=dag_n2 or hop_batch; budget<=8k.
- profile=temporal → hard; hops=2; temporal; budget<=8k.

Keep reasons compact and structured with tags; examples:
- {"route":"easy","reason":"named entity; direct attribute; hops=1; answer_type=entity"}
- {"route":"easy","reason":"two named entities; direct relation check; hops=1; answer_type=yes_no"}
- {"route":"hard","reason":"bridge_2hop; unnamed subject; hops=2; topology=hop_batch; answer_type=entity; budget<=8k"}
- {"route":"hard","reason":"temporal bridge; city-of-death → climate stat; hops=2; topology=chain_n2; answer_type=number; budget<=8k"}

